Introduction

In the previous class we explored the use of linear models and REML methods for variance component estimation. Although we opted to not present equations, estimating variance-covariance components in a mixed model context involves a deep understanding in matrix algebra, first derivatives and optimization methods. With the advent of new computational tools this process became less complex and currently breeders/geneticists can focus on the modeling steps per se, using the machinery of some well-established packages/software to implement mixed model.

Below we present a list of computational tools that summarize the computer packages that use REML as their core algorithm and some relevant features. More details are discussed by Covarrubias-Pazaran, 2022 in the Chapter 6 of the book Complex Trait Prediction.

Theory

ASREML-R

An introduction about Asreml-R is presented here. Herein, we will present some general notes:

  • ASReml is a commercial software that fit linear mixed models using REML with average information (AI) algorithm.
  • ASReml refers to the standalone software with the core written in Fortran. While ASReml-R refers to the R-package that reads the output from ASReml-SA back into R.
  • Asreml-r requires a license from VSN International
  • Basic syntax structure of ASReml-R:
asreml(response ~ fixed_expr, random=~ random_expr, rcov=~ rcov_expr)
  • Random effects are specified in the argument random
  • Residual effects are specified in the argument rcov

Example

library(asreml)
fit1 <- asreml(Yield ~ Site, random=~ Site:Geno, data = dat)
  • Site is a fixed effect
  • Site:Geno is the interaction effect
  • summary(fit1): large list with all results from the fitted model
  • summary(fit1)$varcomp: variance parameter estimates
  • coef(fit1)$fixed: fixed effects (eBLUE) for site
  • coef(fit1)$random: random effects (eBLUP) for the interaction
  • data: should be presented as a data.frame

Some functions

  • plot(fit1): we can plot the diagnostic of the model
  • wald(fit1): inference for fixed effects (Wald Test)
  • lrt(fit2,fit1): residual likelihood test to compare to nested models
  • predict(fit1,classify="Geno")$predictions$pval: predict the adjusted means for fixed and random terms

Convergence issues

  • update(fit1): run more iterations to archive the convergence
  • Decrease the stepsize=0.01 in the argument of the asreml function
  • Use initial values (init) in the argument of the asreml function

Some important tips for memory space

  • Try to increase the workspace="10gb", when fitting LMM using the asreml function
  • Increase the pworkspace="10gb" when using the predict function
  • Be careful to check your system monitor to track your RAM memory

More details on goodness-of-fit

Testing the importance of some source of variation in a model is common in any statistical analyses to make inference. For example, in the ANOVA context, we can check the importance of the genotypic effect by contrasting with the residual using the F test. In a similar way, I could fit a model contemplating the genotypic effect (here called as ful model) and an alternative model without the genotypic effect (reduced model). Intuition behind is not complex, if the genotypic effect is an important source of variation in the data set, when we compare full vs.Â reduced model, we will differences in the goodness-of-fit of the model.

But how to compare the goodness-of-fit statistics? Here, we need remember some concepts, including the likelihood. Technically, a likelihood function is the joint probability of the observed data viewed as a function of the parameters of the chosen statistical model. Hence, how well a sample provides support for particular values of a parameter in a model. In another words, intuitively we can imagine that, if the inclusion of the genotypic effect (i.e, full model) can provides more support to explain the phenotypic variation, the full model will have higher likelihood than the reduced model and therefore should be considered. This job is done by the likelihood-ratio test

\[LRT = -2 ln \dfrac{L_{red}}{L_{full}}\]

  • The likelihood-ratio test assesses the goodness of fit of two competing statistical models based on the ratio of their likelihoods, specifically one found by maximization over the entire parameter space and another found after imposing some constraint. If the constraint (i.e., the null hypothesis) is supported by the observed data, the two likelihoods should not differ by more than sampling error.[1] Thus the likelihood-ratio test tests whether this ratio is significantly different from one, or equivalently whether its natural logarithm is significantly different from zero ref.

Good news about the LRT is because its statistic follows an approximated \(\chi^2\) distribution with degrees of freedom equal to the difference in the number of estimated variance components between both models. So, at the end of the analyses, we can draw conclusions based on a p.valor (i.e, when the pvalue is very small we have statistics evidences that both models are differences and therefore we should choose the model with higher likelihood associated).

In asreml-R, we can use the following function to run the LRT:

lrt.asreml(null_model, full_model, boundary=FALSE),

Another important metric to compare models is the AIC and BIC. An important assumption for LRT is that both models are nested. When this is not the case, the most common ones used for LMMs are the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC), and the Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC):

\[AIC=-2 \times logL + 2 \times t\]

\[BIC = -2 \times logL + 2 \times t \times log(v)\]

where t is the number of variance components in the model, and v is the residual degrees of freedom. Both AIC and BIC are reasonable goodness-of-fit statistics for comparing nested and non-nested models. As the LRT, both methods are also based on the key idea of comparing likelihood results, but here explicitly weighted by the number of parameters in the model. Such values can be computed using the summary for the fitted model.

Hands-on

For the hands-on, we will use the same data set used in the introduction to mixed model class.

  • Download the Maize Recombination Inbred Lines Data (MaizeRILS.csv), an example from Isik et al., 2017.
    • Link for the example.
    • Description: 62 recombinat inbreed lines (RIL) progeny from the crosses between inbred maize lines B73 and MO17. RILS were grown in experimental units using a RCBD design with two replications and four locations.
library(dplyr)
library(asreml)
# Download the data
maize = read.csv("/home/lferrao/Dropbox (UFL)/classes/QuantitativeGenetics_22/Class3_MixedModelsAsReml/MaizeRILs.csv")
maize$rep = as.factor(maize$rep)
maize$block = as.factor(maize$block)

# ASREML fixed model
m3 = asreml(height ~ rep:location + RIL*location,            data=maize)
